# The `SetVector` Class Template Reference

<DoxygenPage pluginConfig={pluginConfig}>

A vector that has set insertion semantics. <a href="#details">More...</a>

## Declaration

<CodeBlock>template &lt;typename T, typename Vector = SmallVector&lt;T, 0&gt;, typename Set = DenseSet&lt;T&gt;, unsigned N = 0&gt;
class llvm::SetVector&lt;T, Vector, Set, N&gt;</CodeBlock>

## Description {#details}

A vector that has set insertion semantics.

This adapter class provides a way to keep a set of things that also has the property of a deterministic iteration order. The order of iteration is the order of insertion.

The key and value types are derived from the Set and Vector types respectively. This allows the vector-type operations and set-type operations to have different types. In particular, this is useful when storing pointers as &quot;Foo &#42;&quot; values but looking them up as &quot;const Foo &#42;&quot; keys.

No constraint is placed on the key and value types, although it is assumed that <a href="#a692c0253127bfefd5af29b4d2d43de22">value&#95;type</a> can be converted into <a href="#aecccf73c9133577d233737080c5bd91c">key&#95;type</a> for insertion. Users must be aware of any loss of information in this conversion. For example, setting <a href="#a692c0253127bfefd5af29b4d2d43de22">value&#95;type</a> to float and <a href="#aecccf73c9133577d233737080c5bd91c">key&#95;type</a> to int can produce very surprising results, but it is not explicitly disallowed.

The parameter N specifies the &quot;small&quot; size of the container, which is the number of elements upto which a linear scan over the Vector will be used when searching for elements instead of checking Set, due to it being better for performance. A value of 0 means that this mode of operation is not used, and is the default value.

Definition at line 57 of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/adt/setvector-h">SetVector.h</a>.

### remove&#95;if() {#a14d9be6f03ca789eb7489fa89273aa40}

<MemberDefinition
  template={<>template &lt;typename UnaryPredicate&gt;</>}
  prototype={<>bool llvm::SetVector&lt; T, Vector, Set, N &gt;::remove&#95;if (UnaryPredicate P)</>}
  labels = {["inline"]}>
Remove items from the set vector based on a predicate function.

This is intended to be equivalent to the following code, if we could write it:


<ProgramListing>

<CodeLine><span class="doxyHighlight"><a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/m68k/#ab3a288f2953d8eca3e363959fc2cf38ea5206560a306a2e085a437fd258eb57ce">V</a>.erase(<a href="#a14d9be6f03ca789eb7489fa89273aa40">remove&#95;if</a>(V, <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/option/option-cpp/#a04665169063c8ca1f2ea96c27fc7c2b2">P</a>), <a href="/docs/api/namespaces/llvm/m68k/#ab3a288f2953d8eca3e363959fc2cf38ea5206560a306a2e085a437fd258eb57ce">V</a>.end());</span></CodeLine>

</ProgramListing>


However, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/setvector">SetVector</a> doesn&#39;t expose non-const iterators, making any algorithm like remove&#95;if impossible to use.


<SectionUser title="Returns">
true if any element is removed.
</SectionUser>
